Information Sheet for Participation in a Research Study Principal Investigator:
Shannon E. Weaver, Ph.D.Student Researcher: Tong
Shen.Study Title:  Influence of Conflict Management and Patterns
of Interaction Within Family of Origin on Current Young Adult Romantic
Relationship Expectations and Experiences. Overview
of the Research 
You are being asked to
provide consent to participate in a research study. Participation is voluntary.
This research is being done to better understand the relationship between patterns of interaction and conflict management in your family of origin and
current romantic relationship expectations and experiences. Participation will involve approximately 25
minutes of your time. You will be asked to complete an online survey. This
study contains minimal risks. There
may be benefits from participation as it might bring increased insights
of your relationships with your romantic partners and parents. A more detailed description
of this research follows. Introduction You are invited to participate in a research study to investigate
the connection between patterns of interaction and conflict management in your
family of origin and current romantic relationship expectations and
experiences. Why is this study being done? The purpose of this research study is to explore how various
patterns of interaction in one’s family of origin influence current romantic
relationship expectations and experiences. Of specific focus are processes
surrounding management of conflict between parents and parental support within the family system
and their relation to current perceptions of relational efficacy, satisfaction,
trust and communication/conflict management in romantic relationships. While
such a focus has been largely understudied, indications are that such a link
exists, but the manner in which influences occur is unclear. This study will help to reveal the relationship. This study will
also conduct a cross-cultural comparison between young adults in the U.S. and
China. What
are the study procedures?  What will I be
asked to do? You will be asked to do an online questionnaire that will take about
25 minutes to complete. This survey will ask about patterns of interaction and
conflict management between your parents and within your family as well as
various aspects of your current or past romantic relationships. What are the risks or inconveniences of the
study?   This study will be carried out anonymously and contains minimal
risks. While this survey deals with potentially sensitive topics such as
conflict management within family of origin, it is not intended to elicit an
emotional response or psychological distress but rather introspection into these
relationships. What
are the benefits of the study? This study will contribute to the small but
growing literature surrounding child and adolescent experiences of family
interaction and its impact on young adult romantic relationships. You
may benefit from this research when you answer the questionnaire as it might
bring increased insights of your relationships with your romantic partners and
parents. Will
I receive payment for participation?  Are
there costs to participate? There are no costs to participate. You will be eligible to enter a
drawing to win a $50 Amazon Gift Card! Four prizes of $50 will be awarded. How will my personal information be protected? Data collection instruments will not contain information that could
readily identify participants (i.e., identifying information). You should also
know that the UConn Institutional Review Board (IRB) and Research Compliance
Services may inspect study records as part of its auditing program, but these
reviews will only focus on the researchers and not on your responses or
involvement. The IRB is a group of people who review research studies to
protect the rights and welfare of research participants. Can
I stop being in the study and what are my rights? You do not have to be in this study if you do not want to. If you
agree to be in the study, but later change your mind, you may drop out at any
time. There are no penalties or consequences of any kind if you decide that you
do not want to participate.
Whom do I contact if I have
questions about the study? Take as long as you like before you make a decision. We will be
happy to answer any question you have about this study. If you have further
questions about this study or if you have a research-related problem, you may
contact the principal investigator, Dr. Shannon Weaver at (860) 486-4684 or the
student researcher Tong Shen at tshen@uconn.edu. If you have questions
concerning your rights as a research participant, you may contact the
University of Connecticut Institutional Review Board (IRB) at 860-486-8802 or irb@uconn.edu. Do you agree to participate in this research study?
